  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can you use Roku to browse the internet?",
  "response": "Roku devices are primarily designed for streaming media content and do not have built-in web browsers for general internet browsing. However, there are a few ways you can access web content on a Roku:\n\n### 1. **Using the Roku Mobile App**\nYou can use the Roku mobile app on your smartphone or tablet as a remote control and also to browse the internet. Here\u2019s how:\n\n- **Download the Roku App**: Available for iOS and Android devices.\n- **Connect to Your Roku**: Open the app and connect it to your Roku device.\n- **Use the Browser Feature**: The app includes a feature called \"Play on Roku\" that allows you to send web videos from your phone to your Roku. While it's not a full web browser, it can play supported video formats from web pages.\n\n### 2. **Third-Party Channels with Browser Functionality**\nSome third-party channels on Roku have limited browsing capabilities. Channels like \"Web Video Cast\" or \"Screen Save\" can open certain websites and play media from them. Here\u2019s how to use them:\n\n- **Add the Channel**: Go to the Roku Channel Store, search for the channel, and add it to your Roku.\n- **Enter URLs**: Use the channel to enter the URL of the website you want to visit. Note that these channels may not support all websites and functionalities.\n\n### 3. **Screen Mirroring**\nIf you have a compatible device, you can mirror your screen to your Roku and then use the browser on your device. Here\u2019s how:\n\n- **Enable Screen Mirroring on Roku**: Go to Settings > System > Screen Mirroring and enable it.\n- **Mirror Your Device**: On your smartphone, tablet, or computer, enable screen mirroring (often called \"Cast\" or \"Screen Mirroring\") and select your Roku device.\n- **Use Your Device\u2019s Browser**: Open your device's web browser and navigate to the websites you want to visit. The content will be mirrored on your Roku-connected TV.\n\n### Limitations to Consider\n- **No Native Browser**: Roku does not come with a native web browser, so you won\u2019t be able to browse the internet in the traditional sense directly on the Roku device.\n- **Limited Functionality**: Third-party channels and screen mirroring can be hit-or-miss in terms of functionality and compatibility with different websites.\n\n### Conclusion\nWhile Roku is not designed for general internet browsing, you can still access web content through the Roku mobile app, third-party channels, or screen mirroring. Each method has its own set of limitations, so the best approach depends on your specific needs and the devices you have available.",
